Local councils are facing a funding crisis due to government cuts and a chaotic, unfair allocation formula. Leicestershire is the country's worst-funded council, highlighting disparities that threaten essential services. With grants ending by 2020, leaders are now working to create a fairer system based on business rates.
Manchester City manager Pep Guardiola has admitted his first season in England was not good enough. Following a defeat to Chelsea that ended their title hopes, he called the campaign a massive lesson. Despite this being his worst season, Guardiola promised he will be better in the future.
The Welsh government has withdrawn controversial plans for 10 new marine conservation zones after a consultation revealed strongly opposing views. Instead of creating new sites, ministers will now assess the existing 125 protected areas for improvements. Conservation groups criticized the decision as an "embarrassing U-turn" for the government.
London Mayor Boris Johnson announced he will back the campaign for Britain to leave the EU. As a charismatic and popular politician, his decision significantly boosts the "Leave" camp. The move is also seen as positioning him for future leadership of the Conservative party.
A lorry struck a broken-down rail replacement bus on the A34 in Oxfordshire. Three of the fifty passengers were hospitalized for their injuries, with one person sustaining serious wounds. The incident closed the major road for several hours, causing significant traffic delays during the investigation.
Scottish boxer Ricky Burns, whose career was considered to be in decline, made a stunning comeback by defeating Michele Di Rocco. The victory made him the first Scot to win world titles at three different weights, a historic achievement. Despite his success, the humble champion celebrated by wanting a burger.
Severe cuts to council budgets are causing a crisis in adult social care, according to a survey of senior officials. Care providers are struggling to hire and retain staff, while the number of people needing support continues to grow. This has led to warnings of unsustainable services.
Terminally ill actor Brian Rix has publicly reversed his stance on assisted dying, a law he previously opposed. Citing his own constant discomfort, he now believes people in his situation should have a choice. He has urged lawmakers to change the law to allow for a peaceful, legal death.
A significant arms cache, including rockets and mines, was discovered in a County Antrim forest. Police believe the weapons belonged to dissident republicans and were ready to be deployed. The seizure is considered one of the most significant in recent years and has undoubtedly saved lives.
Failing electronic systems have severely delayed Kenya's presidential election count, forcing officials to deliver paper results by hand. This has caused widespread public anxiety as the nation awaits the final outcome. Provisional results show Uhuru Kenyatta leading his main opponent, Raila Odinga, in the tightly contested race.
Formula 1 driver Maria de Villota has lost her right eye following a serious crash during a test drive. Her race car collided with a support truck, causing severe head and facial injuries that required a lengthy operation. She remains in a critical but stable condition.
The US Supreme Court upheld President Obama’s healthcare law in a 6-3 decision, preserving federal tax subsidies. This ruling ensures millions of Americans can maintain affordable health insurance, cementing a major presidential legacy. Despite the decision, Republicans have vowed to continue their efforts to repeal the law.
A new Russian law requires popular bloggers to register as media outlets and conform to their regulations. Internet companies must also store user data on Russian servers, making it accessible to the government. Critics have condemned the move as a draconian crackdown on internet freedom and free expression.
Morocco has rejoined the African Union after a 32-year absence over the disputed territory of Western Sahara. While Morocco sees the move as strategic for its economic interests, Western Sahara officials hope it will advance a long-promised referendum on independence, which the AU is expected to support.
After an electric storm temporarily halted Glastonbury, headliners Arcade Fire revived the festival with a party atmosphere. Their energetic performance featured dancers and confetti cannons, lifting revellers' spirits with a series of anthems. Frontman Win Butler described the celebratory two-hour show as a career highlight for the band.
The ancient honey-based beverage, mead, is experiencing a modern resurgence in the United States. Inspired by the craft beer movement, hundreds of new meaderies are producing diverse and refined styles. This growing industry is now challenging old perceptions of the drink as being overly sweet.
This article previews Lady Gaga’s Super Bowl show by revisiting memorable halftime performances from history. It recalls iconic moments from stars like Michael Jackson, Beyoncé, and Janet Jackson, whose controversial performance inspired YouTube’s creation. These examples illustrate the show's evolution into a massive and culturally significant spectacle.
US President Barack Obama criticized David Cameron for becoming "distracted" after the 2011 Libya intervention, which he now calls "a mess." Obama said he expected more from European allies in the aftermath and had also warned the UK to meet its defence spending commitments. Downing Street defended the intervention.
Dawn Purvis is stepping down as programme director of the Marie Stopes clinic, Northern Ireland's first private provider of early medical abortions. Having led the clinic since its 2012 launch, she feels it is now well-established. Purvis will transition to a new role on the clinic's advisory board.
Ten-man Inverness Caledonian Thistle fell four points adrift at the bottom of the league after a 3-0 defeat by St Johnstone. The hosts had Larnell Cole sent off before late goals from Liam Craig and Graham Cummins sealed the result, deepening the club's relegation fears.
The Scottish government is updating its Named Person child wellbeing scheme following a legal challenge. The UK Supreme Court previously ruled its information-sharing proposals breached privacy rights, despite supporting the scheme's intent. Ministers remain committed and will now announce the next steps to implement the revised plan.
Neil Lennon’s appointment as Hibernian manager is a mutually beneficial move for both parties. The role offers Lennon a stable club with a talented, cup-winning squad to rejuvenate his career. In return, Hibs gain a high-profile, proven manager tasked with securing their primary goal of promotion.
UK manufacturing activity contracted in April for the first time in three years, raising fears for the economy. Firms blamed the decline on soft domestic demand, a fall in new overseas business, and EU referendum uncertainty. This slowdown is now causing job losses and is expected to drag on GDP growth.
Police have launched a murder inquiry after prison officer Adrian Ismay died from injuries sustained in a bomb attack. A dissident republican group claimed responsibility for the explosion, which occurred under his van. A post-mortem confirmed the bombing was the direct cause of death, and one man has been charged.
UK Prime Minister David Cameron is hosting a London summit to make fighting corruption a top international priority. He calls corruption an "enemy of progress," aiming for leaders to pledge to expose and punish perpetrators. The first-of-its-kind meeting will gather politicians, businesses, and global organizations to act.
An investigation has found some doctors in England are being offered financial incentives to reduce patient referrals to hospitals. The NHS schemes aim to cut costs by limiting appointments for scans and specialist consultations. Critics fear this could compromise patient care, while health groups defend it as promoting efficiency.
A Chinese woman underwent repeated plastic surgery after her husband allegedly divorced her for having a "fat face." She later sued the hospital for complications, but settled for a small amount. The unverified story went viral, sparking widespread online debate and criticism of both the woman and her ex-husband.
A Hertfordshire council is reactivating its Coronation Fountain for Jubilee and Olympic celebrations despite a hosepipe ban. The council is purchasing non-potable water from a local landscaping company to fill the landmark. This sustainable solution ensures the town looks its best without using precious drinking water supplies.
Harper Lee, author of the beloved classic *To Kill a Mockingbird*, famously never wrote another novel. According to a close friend, she refused to endure the intense loss of privacy that came with fame a second time. Lee also stated she had already said everything she wanted to.
Britain's Adam Peaty defended his 50m breaststroke title at the World Aquatics Championships, completing a "double-double" after also retaining his 100m crown. His winning time of 25.99 seconds was just short of the world record he set in the semi-final. This dominant performance secured his second gold.
The government is proposing life sentences for causing death by careless driving while under the influence. However, the parents of one victim feel this does not go far enough. They believe offenders should face manslaughter charges, arguing that drink-driving is not a "careless" act.
Nine British nationals, including four children, have been detained in Turkey near the Syrian border. The group was allegedly attempting to enter Syria illegally, although their intentions remain unclear. Following their capture, they are being held by Turkish authorities and are now awaiting deportation to the UK.
A North Yorkshire church is struggling with a protected bat colony soiling its historic interior. Despite spending £10,000 on heated lofts to lure them away, the bats have refused to move. The congregation is now left with an appalling smell and ongoing damage to the building.
Baltimore's mayor has fired Police Commissioner Anthony Batts, citing a major crime surge and distractions over his leadership. The dismissal follows recent riots and criticism from the police union over the department's handling of the unrest. Deputy Kevin Davis will now serve as the interim police chief.
Asghar Buksh admitted killing his wife of 25 years by striking her with a heavy object as she slept. He pleaded guilty to culpable homicide on the grounds of diminished responsibility, with psychiatrists confirming he suffered an acute stress disorder. The court heard their marriage had failed.
UKIP’s ruling body rejected a call from activists to deselect Welsh assembly member Michelle Brown over her conduct. The party stated the complaint did not follow the proper disciplinary process, dismissing the activists as a small group. The committee also approved 11 candidates for its leadership contest.
A trial has begun for Chinese cult members who beat a woman to death in a McDonald’s. The victim was attacked after refusing to give her phone number to the group, who were attempting to recruit new members. The brutal murder sparked public outrage and a government crackdown.
After a dramatic Pakistan collapse sparked by debutant Adil Rashid's five wickets, England were set an unlikely target of 99 to win. The tourists aggressively chased the total but were ultimately beaten by the fading light in Abu Dhabi. The match ended in a draw, with England finishing just 25 runs short.
Archaeologists have discovered a 6,000-year-old home near Stonehenge, built within the hollow of a fallen tree. Its inhabitants used the large stump as a wall and heated stones for warmth. Experts now fear a proposed road tunnel will destroy the archaeologically significant site.
Egyptian activists used social media to spark pro-democracy protests, but the movement quickly evolved into real-life activism in Tahrir Square. They emphasize that technology was only a tool for the real network of people. The revolution's true force was citizens uniting in person to demand freedom.
Edinburgh's winter festivals generated over £241 million for the city's economy during the 2014/15 season. The Christmas and Hogmanay celebrations attracted nearly one million visitors over a six-week period. This revenue directly benefited local businesses in retail, accommodation, food, and entertainment, rather than the event organisers.
Ailing department store BHS faces an imminent decision on its future after entering administration and threatening 11,000 jobs. A surprise bid led by retail veteran Greg Tufnell has emerged as the front-runner to acquire the chain. If a deal is not struck, the business faces liquidation.
A new service could use DNA from dog mess to identify owners who fail to clean it up. Councils would require owners to register their dog's DNA on a database using a simple mouth swab. This allows abandoned waste to be tested and matched, leading to the owner being traced.
Scotland's sports funding faces a 20% cut over three years, a move the national agency calls "heartbreaking." The reduction is blamed on lower government spending and a drop in National Lottery sales. This has sparked concerns over the impact on elite athletes and potential job losses.
Welsh political parties are preparing for the next assembly election. Buoyed by recent success and new voter data, the Conservatives feel confident, while Welsh Labour analyzes its poor performance and internal dissent. Plaid Cymru and the Liberal Democrats are also regrouping after failing to make electoral gains.
A campaign group warns that teenagers in Scottish foster care are moved too often, causing harmful instability. Research shows almost half are with their third family, prompting an urgent call for 750 new carers. Finding stable homes is crucial for children's wellbeing, especially for vulnerable teens.
Scientists have used historical Chinese documents to track the decline of the rare Hainan gibbon. The records show the apes were once widespread across China but began disappearing 150 years ago, corresponding with human expansion. Today, fewer than 30 of these primates survive in the wild.
All four schools run by a Telford academy trust have been placed in special measures following Ofsted inspections. Inspectors criticised inadequate teaching, weak leadership, and a lack of support from the trust for the schools' decline. The schools are now considering alternative sponsors to help address the failures.
Over one million EU citizens have signed a petition opposing trade deals with the United States and Canada. Campaigners argue the agreements threaten democracy by allowing foreign companies to sue governments over policy changes. They also fear the deals will lower environmental, social, and consumer protection standards.
Global spirits giant Diageo is investing in Australian distillery Starward Whisky through its Distill Ventures unit. The funding will help increase production and expand the Melbourne-based brand into new international export markets. This move capitalizes on the growing global recognition of Australian whisky and marks Distill's second investment.
Oxford's Ruskin College is cutting several degree programs, citing financial pressures and low student numbers. Students argue this betrays the college's founding principle of providing higher education for working-class and mature adults. The principal defended the decision, stating the college remains committed to adult education but is renewing its approach.
An inquest into the 1976 Kingsmill massacre has been delayed because the senior coroner is retiring with no replacement appointed. This highlights a wider problem of resource shortages stalling numerous Troubles-era cases in Northern Ireland. Victims' families are demanding action, stating justice has been denied for decades.
Rare Leonardo da Vinci drawings from the Queen's royal collection are now on display at Nottingham Castle. The exhibition features a wide range of works, including portraits, anatomical sketches, and technical designs. These drawings, originally acquired by Charles II, are considered among the most brilliant ever created.
